The paper deals with the communication complexity of distributed optimization problems, which involves the exchange of information between different nodes in a network. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves the use of information theory techniques to analyze the communication complexity, which suggests that it may also belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of sampling and sketching techniques in earlier work on distributed optimization, which suggests that it may belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also involves the use of optimization techniques to solve the distributed optimization problems, which suggests that it may belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the analysis of the communication complexity of linear systems and linear programming, which suggests that it may also belong to the Numerical Analysis (cs.NA) sub-category.
